===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
[[File:Oracle Bone Script Di Variants.jpg|thumb|280px|Various forms of {{lang|zh|帝}} in {{w|Oracle Bone Script}}.]]

{{liushu|p}}: Depicts a flower calyx — the structure joining blossom to stem; original form of {{och-l|蒂|calyx; peduncle|tr=*tˤes}}. The calyx is at once the apex of the stalk and the base supporting the flower, an image that naturally motivated extension to "supreme arbiter; God."

Corroborated by a phonosemantic cluster around *tˤe(C): {{och-l|諦|to ascertain|tr=*tˤeh}}, {{och-l|堤|base; embankment|tr=*tˤe}}, {{och-l|締|to bind fast|tr=*dˤeh}}, {{och-l|題|apex; forehead|tr=*dˤe}}, {{och-l|地|ground|tr=*lˤeh}} ({{lang|zh|地，底也…亦言諦也}}) — all converging on "foundational support" and "firm establishment."

Alternative proposals: a bundle of sacrificial firewood or an altar (→ {{och-l|禘|great sacrifice|tr=*dˤeh}}); a circumpolar asterism centered on the north celestial pole ({{zh-ref|Pankenier, 2004}}).

''{{w|Shuowen}}'' erroneously analyzes the character as {{Han compound|丄|朿|ls=psc|c1=s|c2=p|t1=up; above|nocap=1}}.

===Etymology===
From {{inh|zh|sit-pro||*teɣ|God}}; compare {{cog|bo|ཐེ|t=celestial gods of the Bon religion}}, {{cog|kac|tr=mə³¹-tai³³|t=god of the sky}}, {{cog|tbq-bdg-pro|*mɯ-Dai⁴||spirit; god}} ({{zh-ref|Coblin, 1986}}; {{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}; {{zh-ref|Sagart, 2011}}). Cognate with {{och-l|禘|a kind of sacrifice}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

Alternatively, {{zh-ref|Sagart (1999)}} derives it from a root {{m|und|*tek||to be master over; to rule over}}, whence also {{och-l|適|tr=*ᵃtek|to rule; to control}}, {{och-l|嫡|tr=*ᵃtek|son of principal wife}}.

